Within the Circus radiation, Northern Harrier is likely sister to the Hen Harrier (C. cyaneus), with which it was lumped from a period in the early 1900's until 2017, when the American Ornithological Society's North American Checklist Committee voted to split them (17). Some authorities have also included C. cinereus, the Cinereous Harrier of South America, with C. cyaneus and C. hudsonius, or grouped the three species into a superspecies (e.g., 18), but mitochondrial DNA sequence data suggests that this species may be distantly related to C. cyaneus (12).

Pale-legged Hornero (Furnarius leucopus) is closely related to Wing-banded Hornero (Furnarius figulus) and Pale-billed Hornero (Furnarius torridus) (18, 19), though relationships of the recently recognized Caribbean Hornero (Furnarius longirostris) and Pacific Hornero are not fully resolved, as these taxa have not been included in most studies. In one phylogeny, Pale-legged Horneroappeared to be sister to Wing-banded Hornero, with these two species in turn sister to Pale-billed Hornero (18). In another study, Pacific Hornero at least was included, and it was part of this same clade, but relationships were not entirely resolved (19). Caribbean Hornero does not appear to have been included in any molecular phylogenetic study, but is presumably closely related to these species. Further work is needed to clarify relationships among Furnarius horneros.

Molecular phylogenetic analyses have shown that the Yellow-browed Bulbul is closely related to Hemixos (28), where it appears to be nested within what is currently recognized as Hemixos (24). In a study that sampled multiple Hemixos species using both mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequence data, the Yellow-browed Bulbul appeared to be sister to the Cinereous Bulbul (Hemixos cinereus) (24). Together, both the Yellow-browed Bulbul and Cinereous Bulbul appear to be sister to the Ashy Bulbul (Hemixos flavala) and Chestnut Bulbul (Hemixos castanonotus). Another study that did not sample multiple Hemixos species found that the Yellow-browed Bulbul appeared to be sister to the Ashy Bulbul (28).

The relationships of Ixos sumatranus are not fully resolved, and does not appear to have been included in recent molecular phylogenetic studies, but is presumably closely related to Ixos virescens, with which it was formerly considered conspecific.
Curate "Revisiting the systematic position of the enigmatic Nicobar Bulbul (Ixos nicobariensis)"

The species has no extant sister species, having diverged from sister lineages during the late Miocene, an estimated 7.5 million years ago, making it the earliest bulbul lineage in Peninsular India (4).. Mixornis prillwitzi has not been sampled in any molecular phylogeny, so its relationships are not well resolved. It is presumably closely related to Gray-cheeked Tit-Babbler (Mixornis flavicollis), with which it was previously considered conspecific. However, a vocal analysis found that Mixornis prillwitzi had a song that was nearly indistinguishable from Bold-striped Tit-Babbler (Mixornis bornensis), suggesting that it is possibly more closely related to that species than to Mixornis flavicollis (3). In a molecular phylogenetic analysis that included the other species of Mixornis, Mixornis flavicollis was found to be sister to both Mixornis bornensis and Pin-striped Tit-Babbler (Mixornis gularis) (4).

The relationships of Cyornis camarinensis have yet to be conclusively resolved but it is very similar to the Palawan Blue Flycatcher (Cyornis lemprieri) in structure and all plumages (10). For now, it is tentatively grouped within a subset of 15 unplaced Cyornis species in the most recent synthetic phylogeny of Muscicapidae (19). The fact that both Cyornis camarinensis and Cyornis lemprieri are Philippine endemics may make a sister relationship between these two seem especially likely, although Luzon and Palawan share few if any narrow endemics, and most modern global lists do not place them together in the linear sequence, Wolters being an exception (20). Given its similarity and former conspecificity, the speciesâ€™ closest relative is almost certainly the Blue-breasted Blue Flycatcher (Cyornis herioti).

Relationships of Enicurus borneensis with respect to White-crowned Forktail (Enicurus leschenaulti), with which it was formerly considered conspecific, are not well resolved. The two taxa are indeed closely related, but Enicurus borneensis may be embedded within Enicurus leschenaulti, though relationships are not well-supported, and three clades are generally recovered in the group: one representing Enicurus borneensis, one representing Javan populations of Enicurus leschenaulti, and one comprised of lowland Sundaic populations (5, 4).

Often considered conspecific with Forest Rock-Thrush (Monticola sharpei), and recent molecular studies argue for this based on low genetic divergence (1, 2, 3); however, differs markedly in morphology, having breast rich orange-rufous vs dull blue-gray (i.e., transition in color is at lower throat; 3); rich blue-gray crown to nape sharply demarcated from dark chestnut-brown back to rump and scapulars vs duller (olive-tinged) blue-gray crown gently grading to dark gray-tinged olive-brownish back to rump (3); and larger size (effect size for both bill and wing in males 2.13; score 2); female mirrors male breast pattern by replacing long pale and dark streaks of Forest Rock-Thrush with rusty breastband and broad straw-colored streaks

Originally described as a distinct species, the Atlas Wheatear has long been considered conspecific with the Northern Wheatear. Its taxonomic status is still debated, and available genetic evidence suggests very low divergence; mitochondrial DNA, both traditional sequence data and whole mitochondrial genome data, show Oenanthe seebohmi as embedded within Oenanthe oenanthe, and fail to find any of the subspecies as genetically distinct. These results stand in contrast to differences in plumage, as well as ecological differences, which support recognition of the Atlas Wheatear as a distinct species (see Systematics).

Together with Yellow-crowned Flowerpecker, with which it was formerly considered conspecific, Flame-crowned Flowerpecker resembles the Bicolored Flowerpecker (Dicaeum bicolor) in its bill shape (but this is even heavier in the present species) and in color pattern (although Bicolored Flowerpecker lacks the bright color patch). It also resembles the Cebu Flowerpecker (Dicaeum quadricolor), to which it and Bicolored Flowerpecker have been speculated to be closely related (5). Flame-crowned Flowerpecker and Yellow-crowned Flowerpecker together were confirmed, with strong support, to be sister to Bicolored Flowerpecker (among those taxa in the phylogeny, not including Cebu Flowerpecker), based on mtDNA sequence data and one nuclear intron, and to be members of the Dicaeum clade as opposed to the Prionochilus and Pachyglossa clades that contain most of the other thick-billed flowerpeckers (20, 21).

A molecular phylogeny of Nectariniidae (see Systematics History) suggested that the Amani Sunbird (Hedydipna pallidigaster) and Rufous-winged Sunbird (Cinnyris rufipennis) are sister species (14, 17). This is somewhat unexpected because bill morphology has often been used as a taxonomic character, and Amani Sunbird has a short, unspecialized bill, whereas Rufous-winged Sunbird has a long decurved bill. Mapping bill morphology onto molecular-phylogenetic trees suggested that bill length is labile, with long and short bills having evolved multiple times (14).

The first phylogenetic studies in the genus Anthus, based on cytochrome b DNA sequence data, reported that two of the three subspecies of Anthus hellmayri complex are paraphyletic (14), with nominate hellmayri sister to Paramo Pipit (Anthus bogotensis) and Anthus hellmayri brasilianus sister of this clade. However, additional research using multiple genetic markers which included all three subspecies of the Anthus hellmayri complex reported that the three represent a monophyletic clade and their origin dated from 1.5 to 0.5 million years ago (8). Within this group, the taxa brasilianus and dabbenei were sister, and together these two were sister to nominate hellmayri; Anthus hellmayri in turn appeared to be sister to Anthus bogotensis (8).

notes: Genetic studies have shown that Macaronesia was colonized in a single wave from the mainland; the Azores were colonized first (likely by birds from Europe), with chaffinches then colonizing Madeira followed by the Canary Islands (33, 28, 29, 30). After each successive colonization, the resulting species lost genetic diversity, so that the Canary Islands Chaffinch has the lowest genetic diversity, and the Azores Chaffinch has the highest genetic diversity among these island species, comparable to that of mainland populations (30). Therefore, the Azores Chaffinch appears to be sister to both Madeira Chaffinch and Canary Islands Chaffinch, and together, the three Atlantic islands species are most closely related to the two mainland species, Common Chaffinch and African Chaffinch (30). The ancestor of African Chaffinch and Common Chaffinch diverged from the ancestor of all Macaronesian chaffinch species approximately 0.81 million years ago, with the Azores Chaffinch diverging from the ancestor of the Madeira Chaffinch and the Canary Islands Chaffinch about 0.77 million years ago (30).

However, several authors kept recognizing godmani and affinis as separate species (2, 9, 10, 11, 12), an idea that was recently revisited in light of new data showing reciprocal monophyly in multiple genetic loci between affinis and godmani, as well as diagnosable differences in plumage and song (3). The most comprehensive phylogenetic systematic interrogation of Dacnis species was not able to sample the Scarlet-breasted Dacnis. Thus, molecular systematics has not been able to test the hypothesis that the Scarlet-breasted Dacnis is indeed a species of Dacnis (Burns et al. 2014). The Scarlet-breasted Dacnis is morphologically quite different from other species in the genus, and Burns (et al. 2014) regarded its placement as uncertain. Superficially its plumage resembles that of the Tit-like Dacnis (Xenodacnis parina), which is placed in Diglossinae (Burns et al. 2014). In addition, Storer (1970) doubted whether Dacnis berlepschi was closely related to other species of Dacnis, and Wolters (1975â€“1982) considered Xenodacnis parina and D. berlepschi closely related, placing both within the genus Xenodacnis. Following current taxonomy, the genus Dacnis includes the Scarlet-breasted Dacnis and 8 others species in the genus (Burns et al. 2016). Within Thraupidae (tanagers), Dacnis is placed in the subfamily Dacninae along with the Swallow Tanager (Tersina viridis) and Cyanerpes honeycreepers, though how these genera are related to each other remains unsupported (Burns et al. 2003, Burns et al. 2014).
